{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640133"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17807"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17807"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72430"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10173"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24553"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72430"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe epidermis of human skin is a stratified squamous epithelium that provides protection against environmental damage, dehydration, and pathogen invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct sequence of epidermal layers from deepest to most superficial?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basale, granulosum, spinosum, lucidum, corneum","Basale, spinosum, granulosum, lucidum, corneum","Basale, lucidum, granulosum, spinosum, corneum","Basale, spinosum, lucidum, granulosum, corneum","Basale, corneum, spinosum, granulosum, lucidum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of epidermal layers from deep to superficial is \u003Cstrong\u003Estratum basale, spinosum, granulosum, lucidum, and corneum\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents the progression of keratinocyte differentiation as cells move towards the surface.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect sequences can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasale, granulosum, spinosum, lucidum, corneum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the stratum spinosum appears before the granulosum during differentiation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasale, lucidum, granulosum, spinosum, corneum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the stratum lucidum appears after both the spinosum and granulosum layers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasale, spinosum, lucidum, granulosum, corneum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the stratum granulosum must appear before the lucidum layer.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasale, corneum, spinosum, granulosum, lucidum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the stratum corneum is the most superficial layer and cannot appear between deeper layers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKeratinocytes begin in the stratum basale as stem cells, then differentiate and migrate upward through each layer, ultimately becoming the dead, flattened cells of the stratum corneum. This process takes approximately 28 days.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The epidermis consists of five distinct layers: stratum basale, spinosum, granulosum, lucidum, and corneum.","Keratinocytes differentiate and migrate from the stratum basale to the stratum corneum over approximately 28 days.","The stratum corneum provides the main barrier function of the skin through its structure of dead keratinocytes and lipids."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17807"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:39:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:40:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10521"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72430"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}